nt-while-Brexit-could-swing-Scots-behind-a-second-independence-referendum-Yes-vote.aspx Ipsos Mori/STV] || 1,000 ||style=\"background: rgb(1, 223, 116);\"|'''54%'''||39%||7%||style=\"background: rgb(0, 129, 66); color: white;\"|15%\n|}\n\n===On the prospect of a second referendum===\n==== 2017 ====\nAnalysis of opinion polling from early 2017 by Professor [[John Curtice]] found that around 50% of Scottish voters were opposed to the holding of a second referendum on Scottish independence, with just over a third in support of holding another referendum.<ref>[http://blog.whatscotlandthinks.org/2017/03/does-scotland-want-a-second-independence-referendum/ 'Does Scotland Scotland want a second independence referendum?']</ref>\n\nA September 2017 poll by Survation gave respondents an option of when they thought a second referendum should be held. 22% said that they'd support holding a referendum before Britain leaves the European Union, 13% said around the time Britain leaves the EU, a further 13% said that a referendum should be held a few years following the UK's exit and 8% said a referendum should come after the [[2021 Scottish Parliament election|2021 Scottish Parliamentary elections]]. 37% said that a referendum should never be held on Scottish independence again, with 8% undecided.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://survation.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Final-SDM-VI-Tables-1c0d1h6-080917MBJRFSTJNHCH-I.pdf|title=Voting Intention Poll|work=Survation|date=13 September 2017|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nA Panelbase poll from the same month found that 17% of people thought that a referendum should be held while the UK is negotiating its exit from the European Union, 26% said that a referendum should come once the negotiations had finished, while 58% said that a referendum shouldn't be held before the United Kingdom's exit from the EU.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panelbase.com/media/polls/W7181w14forpublication070917.pdf|title=Sunday Times (W7181w14)|work=Panelbase|date=7 September 2017|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== 2018 ====\nIn January 2018, YouGov found that 54% of people opposed holding a referendum in principle, compared to 36% who supported holding one. These numbers fell when asked whether a referendum should be held following Brexit negotiations, but before the UK leaves the EU, to 51% and 35% respectively. The same poll found that 36% supported holding a referendum once Britain has left the EU, compared to 47% opposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://d25d2506sfb94s.cloudfront.net/cumulus_uploads/document/une1vahaj1/TimesResults_180116_Westminster_Scotland_VI_w.pdf|title=YouGov / The Times Survey Results|work=YouGov|date=12\u201316 January 2018|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nA March 2018 poll by Ipsos Mori found that 42% of Scots supported holding a second referendum within the next three years, compared to 47% who opposed one; 8% said that they neither supported or opposed a referendum being held within this timescale. Support for a referendum was highest among sixteen to thirty-four year-olds, the unemployed, charity workers, council house dwellers and people living in the 20% of most deprived areas in Scotland. Opposition was greatest from people aged over fifty-five, retirees, homeowners and people with no formal qualifications.<ref name=\"Ipsos Mori March 2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ipsos.com/sites/default/files/ct/news/documents/2018-03/scotland-spom-march-2018-tables.pdf|title=Scottish Public Opinion Monitor \u2013 Wave 35|work=Ipsos Mori|date=5\u201311 March 2018|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Opinion polling in the rest of the United Kingdom ===\nIn 2014 a plurality (41%) of people polled in England and Wales thought that Scotland would vote to remain in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news |last=Learmonth |first=Andrew |date=8 July 2016 |title=Majority of Brits believe Scots would vote to exit UK |url=http://www.thenational.scot/news/majority-of-brits-believe-scots-would-vote-to-exit-uk.19740 |newspaper=The National |location= |access-date=8 July 2016 }}</ref> However, an [[Opinium Research LLP|Opinium]] poll carried out 28\u201330 June 2016 showed a marked change, with 69% believing that Scotland would vote for independence in a second referendum, with 16% believing it would vote against independence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ourinsight.opinium.co.uk/sites/ourinsight.opinium.co.uk/files/vi_28_06_2016_v2.pdf |title=Opinium VI 28 06 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704154110/http://ourinsight.opinium.co.uk/sites/ourinsight.opinium.co.uk/files/vi_28_06_2016_v2.pdf |archivedate=4 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nA May 2018 poll, conducted by Panelbase, suggested that 52% of English-born English-based voters would vote to enter into a political union with Scotland if the countries were independent of each other, compared to 58% supporting a union with Wales and 43% with Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wingsoverscotland.com/the-island-within-an-island/|title=The island within an island|date=18 May 2018|accessdate=19 May 2018|publisher=Wings Over Scotland}}</ref> The poll additionally found that 43% of English voters would accept Scotland leaving the United Kingdom as a result of the exit from the European Union, compared to 35% who would oppose this.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wingsoverscotland.com/nations-overboard/|title=Nations Overboard|date=17 May 2018|accessdate=19 May 2018|publisher=Wings Over Scotland}}</ref>\n\n=== Opinion polling in the European Union ===\nPolls conducted by YouGov in July 2016 found majority support in Germany (71%), Denmark (67%), Finland (66%), Sweden (64%) and France (61%) for Scotland becoming an EU member should it become an independent state, with plurality support in EFTA member Norway (46%) and the United Kingdom as a whole (41%).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://yougov.de/news/2016/07/08/nach-der-brexit-entscheidung-deal-or-no-deal/ |title=Nach der Brexit-Entscheidung: Deal or no Deal? |first=Matthias |last=Schmidt |website=yougov.de |publisher=YouGov |date=8 July 2016 |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Unionism in Scotland]]\n*[[Irish reunification]]\n*[[Welsh independence]]\n*[[London independence]]\n*[[All Under One Banner]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Scottish elections}}\n{{United Kingdom European Union membership referendum, 2016}}\n\n[[Category:Consequences of the 2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|Scottish independence]]\n[[Category:Independence referendums|Scottish independence referendum]]\n[[Category:Proposed referendums|Scottish independence referendum]]\n[[Category:Referendums in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scottish independence]]\n", "text_old": "{{PoliticsScotland}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Update|documentation|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Scottish independence protest.jpg|thumb|Pro-independence protest in [[Edinburgh]], 2019]]\nThe [[Scottish Government]] has proposed holding a second referendum on Scottish independence from the [[United Kingdom]] (UK). A [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|referendum on Scottish independence]] was held in 2014, with 55% voting against the proposal. After this, the UK voted to leave the [[European Union]] (EU) in a [[Brexit referendum|2016 referendum]]. One of the reasons cited by those opposed to [[Scottish independence]] during the 2014 campaign was that it would endanger [[Scotland]] being part of the EU. \n\nThe SNP majority [[Scottish Government]] stated in its 2013 white paper on independence that the 2014 referendum would be a \"once in a generation opportunity to follow a different path, and choose a new and better direction for our nation\".<ref name=\"White Paper\">{{cite web|url=https://www2.gov.scot/resource/0043/00439021.pdf|title=SCOTLAND\u02bcS FUTURE YOUR GUIDE TO AN INDEPENDENT SCOTLAND|date=1 November 2013|website=gov.scot|publisher=gov.scot|accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref> Following the election of a Conservative UK government in [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]], a referendum on UK membership of the EU was scheduled for June 2016. The SNP stated in its manifesto for the [[2016 Scottish Parliament election|May 2016 Scottish Parliament election]] that a second independence referendum should be held if there was a material change of circumstances, such as the [[Brexit|UK leaving the EU]].\n\nThe SNP formed a minority government in 2016 with the [[Scottish Parliament]] having a pro-independence majority with the [[Scottish Greens]]. The \"leave\" side won the EU referendum with 52% of the vote across the UK. In Scotland, 62% of votes were to \"remain\" in the EU, with a majority of voters in every local authority area voting \"remain\".\n\nIn March 2017 [[First Minister of Scotland|First Minister]] [[Nicola Sturgeon]] gained the approval of the Scottish Parliament to request a [[Section 30 of the Scotland Act|Section 30 order]] to enable a second independence referendum \"when the shape of the UK's Brexit deal will become clear\", within 18\u201324 months.<ref name=13marchscotgov>{{cite web|url=http://news.gov.scot/news/scotland-must-have-choice-over-future|date=2017-03-13|accessdate=2017-03-13|website=[[Scottish Government]]|title=Scotland must have choice over future}}</ref><ref name=\"2017 request\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-39449459|title=Sturgeon signs independence vote request|date=2017-03-30|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-03-30|language=en-GB}}</ref> Earlier the same month, the UK Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] stated that \"now is not the time\" to discuss another referendum, because the focus should be on \"working together, not pulling apart\" for Brexit negotiations.<ref name=\"Rejected BBC 16Mar2017\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-39293513|title=Scottish independence: Referendum demand 'will be rejected'|date=16 March 2017|website=bbc.com|publisher=BBC|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref> The [[Brexit]] process also met a 10-month delay due to lack of ratification of the exit deal by the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/10/28/brexit-delayed-many-brexit-extensions-10996922/|title=Is Brexit delayed and how many Brexit extensions have there been?|last=Martin|first=Rachael|date=2019-10-28|work=The Metro|access-date=2020-01-01|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, Sturgeon sent an official request to hold an independence referendum to May's successor as prime minister, [[Boris Johnson]]. Sturgeon advocated holding a referendum in 2020 and published a document presenting the democratic case for a referendum alongside proposed amendments to the [[Scotland Act 1998]], including to give the Scottish parliament permanent powers to hold referendums and for UK law to make provisions for self-determination.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/19/nicola-sturgeon-requests-independence-referendum-powers|title=Sturgeon demands independence referendum powers be devolved|last=correspondent|first=Libby Brooks Scotland|date=2019-12-19|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gov.scot/publications/scotlands-right-choose-putting-scotlands-future-scotlands-hands/|title=Scotland's right to choose: putting Scotland's future in Scotland's hands\n|last=Scottish Government|first=|date=2019-12-19|work=The Scottish Government|access-date=2019-12-27|language=en-GB|isbn=9781839604454}}</ref><ref name=\"for 2020\">{{cite news |first= Libby |last=Brooks |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/15/nicola-sturgeon-to-demand-powers-for-2020-referendum |title= Nicola Sturgeon to demand powers for 2020 referendum |work= The Guardian |date= 15 October 2019 |accessdate= 31 December 2019}}</ref> In January 2020, the request was rejected by the UK government, which pointed out that Sturgeon had promised that the 2014 referendum would not be repeated for at least a generation, and that both the Scottish and UK governments had pledged to abide by its outcome.\n\n==History==\n===2014 Scottish independence referendum===\n{{Main|2014 Scottish independence referendum}}\n[[File:Scottish independence referendum results.svg|150px|thumb|Results by council area of the 2014 Scottish independence referendum:<br />{{legend|#24B14C|Yes}}{{legend|#DF0A24|No}}]]\nThe referendum on Scottish independence held on 18 September 2014 saw Scotland vote to remain part of the United Kingdom (UK), with 55% voting against the proposal for Scotland to become an independent country and 45% voting in favour. Uncertainty over Scotland's European Union (EU) membership was a topic in the run-up to the referendum vote.<ref name=\"Clegg 2014\">{{cite web | last= Clegg | first=David | title= Independence referendum: Euro bigwig Jose Manuel Barroso delivers fresh blow to Yes campaign | website= Daily record | date=17 February 2014 | url= http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/politics/independence-referendum-ec-president-jose-3154114 | accessdate= 25 June 2016 | quote=EU membership is another central plank in Salmond's blueprint for independence outlined in the SNP's White Paper last year.}}</ref> The British government and some mainstream political parties argued that remaining in the UK was the only way for Scotland to remain part of the EU.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jun/24/nicola-sturgeon-keep-scotland-eu-independence |title=Nicola Sturgeon needs to keep Scotland in the EU. But how? |first=Lesley|last=Riddoch|authorlink= Lesley Riddoch|date=24 June 2016|work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= https://apnews.com/cace8f31f50245b093e26cdd434d236e |title=Pro-EU Scots, Northern Irish eye UK escape after Brexit vote|date= 24 June 2016|agency= Associated Press}}</ref> The proposed UK referendum on EU membership had already been announced, and was a topic of discussion in the independence debate.<ref name=\"salmond eu\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-28980041 |title=Scottish independence: Alex Salmond says Eurosceptics 'damaging Scotland' |work=BBC News |date=29 August 2014 |accessdate=29 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOther issues, such as the economy, played a large part in the debate. Financial groups, such as the [[Royal Bank of Scotland]] and [[Lloyds Banking Group]], were reported to be considering moving their registered offices to London, as a result of a European law stating that banks should have their head offices in the same member state as its registered office, as well as implying that these offices should be in the location where they conduct most of their activity \u2013 which would be the remainder of the United Kingdom in the event of Scottish independence.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-26455655|title=EU law may force RBS and Lloyds to become English |work= BBC News|date=5 March 2014 |accessdate= 21 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=CELEX:31995L0026:EN:HTML |title=Council Directive 95/26/EC |work= Eur-lex | publisher = Europa |date= 18 July 1995 |accessdate= 21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Scottish Government's official publication on the independence referendum stated that \"It is the view of the current Scottish Government that a referendum is a once-in-a-generation opportunity\",<ref>Scottish Government (November 2013) [http://www.gov.scot/Resource/0043/00439021.pdf  \"Scotland's Future\"]. p. 556.</ref> a point reiterated a few days before the vote by the SNP's then-leader, [[Alex Salmond]], noting the eighteen-year gap between the devolution referenda held in [[1979 Scottish devolution referendum|1979]] and in [[1997 Scottish devolution referendum |1997]] as an example of the generational opportunity.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-29196661|title=Salmond: 'Referendum is once in a generation opportunity'|date=14 September 2014|work=BBC}}</ref> Three months later, Salmond reversed the position, highlighting the UK's EU referendum as a factor.<ref>Kinder, Tabatha (20 December 2014) [http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/second-scottish-independence-referendum-horizon-says-alex-salmond-1480417 \"'A second Scottish independence referendum is on the horizon', says Alex Salmond\"]. ''International Business Times''.</ref> The UK government had also portrayed the independence referendum as once-in-a-generation.<ref>Aitken, Keith (15 October 2012) [http://www.publicfinance.co.uk/news/2012/10/terms-%E2%80%98once-generation%E2%80%99-scottish-independence-referendum-agreed \"Terms of 'once in a generation' Scottish independence referendum agreed\"]. Public Finance. CIPFA.</ref>\n\nThough the proposal for Scotland to become an independent country was voted down in 2014, the referendum resulted in the Scottish Parliament gaining additional powers through the  [[Scotland Act 2016]], which increased the devolved powers in areas such as taxation and some aspects of welfare provision.<ref>{{Cite journal|last= McGarvey |first=Neil|year= 2015 |title= The 2014 Scottish Independence Referendum and Its Aftermath |journal= Social Alternatives |volume= 34 |pages= 34\u201340|via= EBSCOHost}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom general election, 2015===\n{{see also|United Kingdom general election, 2015 (Scotland)}}\n[[File:2015UKelectionMapScotland.svg|right|300px|thumb|Results of the 2015 United Kingdom general election]]\nThe [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 UK general election]] was held on 7 May almost eight months after the independence referendum was held. In their manifesto, the SNP said the following in response to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]]' manifesto pledge promising a referendum on EU membership by the end of 2017 if elected:<ref>/http://votesnp.com/docs/manifesto.pdf}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>The European Union is far from perfect, however, we believe that it is overwhelmingly in Scotland\u2019s interests for us to remain a member, engaging with the institutions as fully as we can, and to argue for reform from within. We will oppose UK withdrawal from the EU and will propose that, in any future referendum, there should be a double majority requirement. Each of the four constituent nations of the UK would have to vote for withdrawal before the UK as a whole could leave the European Union.</blockquote>\n\nThe SNP went on to win 56 of the 59 Scottish seats that were contested in an unprecedented landslide winning 50% of the national vote and left just three unionist MPs in Scotland; [[Scottish Labour Party|Labour]] saw their worst result in Scotland since [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918]], the [[Scottish Liberal Democrats|Liberal Democrats]] fell to their lowest level since [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970]] and the [[Scottish Conservative Party|Conservatives]] received their lowest vote share in Scotland since [[1865 United Kingdom general election|1865]].\n\nAcross the United Kingdom, the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] led by [[David Cameron]] won an unexpected overall majority, their first since 1992 and following their victory passed the [[European Union Referendum Act 2015]] which legislated for the holding of a national UK-wide referendum on EU membership which would be held following the conclusion of a [[United Kingdom renegotiation of European Union membership, 2015\u201316|renegotiation of the UK's membership to the EU]].\n\n===Scottish Parliament election, 2016===\n{{Main|Scottish Parliament election, 2016}}\n[[File:Scottish Election Results 2016.svg|thumb|300px|Results of the 2016 Scottish Parliament election]]\nThe elections to the Scottish Parliament took place on 5 May 2016, seven weeks before the holding of the EU Referendum. In their manifesto for the [[2016 Scottish Parliament election|2016 Scottish elections]], the SNP stipulated conditions under which they would seek a second independence referendum:<ref>[https://www.snp.org/manifesto SNP 2016 manifesto], p. 23</ref>\n\n<blockquote>We believe that the Scottish Parliament should have the right to hold another referendum if there is clear and sustained evidence that independence has become the preferred option of a majority of the Scottish people \u2013 or if there is a significant and material change in the circumstances that prevailed in 2014, such as Scotland being taken out of the EU against our will.</blockquote>\nThe SNP were re-elected in the 2016 election, winning 63 seats in the 129-seat chamber, although the result meant that they no longer held an overall majority.<ref name = \"2016 result\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2016-scotland-36205187 |title=Holyrood 2016: SNP claims 'historic' win but no majority |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 May 2016 |accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref>  The pro-independence [[Scottish Green Party]] won 6 seats,<ref name = \"2016 result\"/> meaning that pro-independence MSPs maintained a majority.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2017/03/scottish-greens-will-back-snp-over-indyref-2 |title=Scottish Greens will back SNP over Indyref 2 |first=Julia |last=Rampen |work=New Statesman |publisher= |date=13 March 2017 |accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Scottish Green Party|Green]] manifesto stipulated that a second referendum should be held if there was public demand for one, rather than as a result of \"calculations of party political advantage\". The party specified that their preferred method of showing support for a referendum was via a public petition, although their manifesto didn't clarify how many signatories there would have to be to receive their support:<ref>[https://greens.scot/sites/default/files/Campaigns/Holyrood%202016/Holyrood%20Manifesto%202016%20%E2%80%93%20RNIB.pdf Scottish Green 2016 manifesto], p. 36</ref>\n\n<blockquote>Citizens should be able to play a direct role in the legislative process: on presenting a petition signed by an appropriate number of voters, citizens should be able to trigger a vote on important issues of devolved responsibility. As we proposed on the first anniversary of the Independence Referendum, this is the Scottish Greens\u2019 preferred way of deciding to hold a second referendum on Independence. If a new referendum is to happen, it should come about by the will of the people, and not be driven by calculations of party political advantage. In such a referendum the Scottish Greens will campaign for independence.</blockquote>\n\n===United Kingdom European Union membership referendum, 2016===\n{{Main|2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum}}\n[[File:United Kingdom European Union referendum 2016 voting area results (Scotland).svg|150px|thumb|Every council area in Scotland returned majority votes in favour of remaining in the [[European Union|EU]], contrasting with other parts of the UK, who ultimately carried the overall [[United Kingdom withdrawal from the European Union|UK leave vote]].<br />{{legend|#ffc010|Remain}}]]\nIn the EU membership referendum held on 23 June 2016, all thirty-two council areas in Scotland voted by a majority for the UK to remain a member of the EU. 62% of Scottish voters voted to remain a member of the EU, with 38% voting to leave. However, 52% of voters across the whole UK voted to leave the European Union, with 48% voting to remain; majorities in England and Wales were in favour of leaving the EU, with majorities in Scotland, Northern Ireland and Gibraltar to remain a member of the EU.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/eu_referendum/results|title=EU Referendum Results|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nBefore the referendum, leading figures with a range of opinions regarding [[Scottish independence]] suggested that in the event the UK as a whole voted to leave the EU but Scotland as a whole voted to remain, a second independence referendum might be precipitated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2016/01/24/nicola-sturgeon-denies-she-has-machiavellian-wish-for-brexit_n_9063372.html|title=Nicola Sturgeon Denies She Has 'Machiavellian' Wish For Brexit|last=Simons|first=Ned|date=24 January 2016|website=The Huffington Post UK|accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2016/01/26/scotland-will-quit-britain-if-uk-leaves-eu-warns-tony-blair_n_9077274.html|title=Scotland Will Quit Britain If UK Leaves EU, Warns Tony Blair|last=Simons|first=Ned|date=26 January 2016|website=The Huffington Post UK|accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref> Former Labour Scottish First Minister [[Henry McLeish]] asserted that he would support Scottish independence under such circumstances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/14194315.Henry_McLeish__I_will_back_Scottish_independence_if_UK_leave_EU_against_Scotland_s_wishes/?ref=rss|title=Henry McLeish: I will back Scottish independence if UK leave EU against Scotland's wishes|date=10 January 2016|website=The Herald|location=Glasgow|accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Scotland exported around three and a half times more to the rest of the UK than to the rest of the EU,<ref name=\"SiU\">{{cite web|title=Scotland, 'Brexit' and the UK|url=https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/scotlandinunion/pages/377/attachments/original/1453372484/Brexit_PDF.pdf?1453372484|publisher=Scotland in Union|accessdate=5 July 2016|date=January 2016}}</ref> while in 2015, that had increased to around four times more to the rest of the UK than to the rest of the EU.<ref>{{cite report |author=The Scottish Government|author-link= |authors= |date=25 January 2017|title=Export Statistics Scotland 2015|url=http://www.gov.scot/Resource/0051/00513335.pdf|publisher= |pages=1\u20132|docket= |access-date=5 February 2017|quote= }}</ref> The pro-union organisation Scotland in Union has suggested that an independent Scotland within the EU would face trade barriers with a post-Brexit UK and face additional costs for re-entry to the EU.<ref name=\"SiU\"/>\n\nA report for the [[European Parliament]] regarding the impact on the United Kingdom's exit from the EU on devolution suggested that \"there now seems to be a consensus that, were Scotland to become independent by legal means, it could join the [European] Union\", something which had been questioned before the 2014 referendum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/IDAN/2017/583118/IPOL_IDA(2017)583118_EN.pdf|title=The Impact of the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union on Scotland, Wales and Gibraltar|work=Directorate General for Internal Policies|date=September 2017|accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the result, on 24 June 2016, the [[Scottish Government]] said officials would begin planning for a second referendum on independence.<ref name=\"nbcnews\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/25/world/europe/brexit-scotland-independence-referendum.html|title=Scotland Says New Vote on Independence Is 'Highly Likely'|date=25 June 2016|work=The New York Times}}</ref> [[Scottish First Minister]] [[Nicola Sturgeon]] said it was \"clear that the people of Scotland see their future as part of the European Union\" and that Scotland had \"spoken decisively\" with a \"strong, unequivocal\" vote to remain in the European Union.<ref name=\"ft2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/06a90f8c-39c0-11e6-a780-b48ed7b6126f.html#axzz4CRXecPen|title=Scots' backing for Remain raises threat of union's demise|first=Mure|last=Dickie|date=24 June 2016|newspaper=Financial Times}}</ref> Sturgeon said it was \"democratically unacceptable\" that Scotland could be taken out of the EU \"against its will\".<ref name=\"nbcnews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/brexit-referendum/scotland-could-seek-independence-again-after-u-k-brexit-vote-n598166|title='Brexit' Triggers New Bid for Scottish Independence|website=[[NBC News]]|last=Jamieson|first=Alastair|date=24 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC 24 June 2016 Sturgeon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-36621030|title=Brexit: Nicola Sturgeon says second Scottish independence vote 'highly likely'|work=BBC News|date=26 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, the Scottish Parliament voted 90 to 34 to oppose the UK leaving the EU and to oppose [[United Kingdom invocation of Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union|invoking Article 50]] in a non-binding vote.<ref name=\"dw17\">[http://www.dw.com/en/scottish-parliament-rejects-brexit-in-non-binding-vote/a-37448650 Scottish parliament rejects Brexit in non-binding vote], ''DW'', 07 February 2017</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom general election, 2017===\n{{Main|United Kingdom general election, 2017 (Scotland)}}\n[[File:2017UKelectionMapScotland.svg|right|300px|thumb|Results of the 2017 United Kingdom general election in Scotland.]]\n\nThe [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 UK general election]] returned a [[hung parliament]] resulting in Theresa May's [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] returning as a minority government through a [[Arrangement between the Conservative Party and the Democratic Unionist Party|pact]] with the [[Democratic Unionist Party]].\n\nThe SNP remained as the third-largest party in the UK [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] with its representation reduced to 35 of the total 59 Scottish MPs. The SNP had 21 fewer seats than they won in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] and its popular vote in Scotland reduced from 50% in 2015 to 37% in 2017 with a lower voter turnout. The Conservatives, who oppose independence, saw their best election in Scotland since 1983, winning 29% of the vote and increasing their seat total to thirteen, compared to one in the previous parliament.\n\nSturgeon stated: \"Undoubtedly the issue of an independence referendum was a factor in this election result, but I think there were other factors in this election result as well\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-40216748|title=General election 2017: Sturgeon says Indyref2 'a factor' in SNP losses|date=9 June 2017|work=BBC}}</ref> Opposition to a second referendum is one of the issues that former SNP MP [[Angus Robertson]] and [[Scottish Conservatives|Scottish Conservative]] leader [[Ruth Davidson]] have attributed to reduced support for the SNP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/06/08/europe/snp-uk-general-election/index.html|title=Scottish referendum in doubt after steep losses for SNP in UK vote|work=CNN|date=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe SNP lost seats that voted for independence. [[Glasgow North East]] was gained by [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] despite consisting mostly of the two Scottish Parliamentary constituencies with the largest support for independence within the [[Glasgow City Council|Glasgow City council area]] \u2013 [[Glasgow Maryhill and Springburn (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Maryhill and Springburn]] and [[Glasgow Provan (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Provan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.glasgow.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=22501&p=0|title=Scottish Independence Referendum 2014 \u2013 Glasgow Partial Total|work=Glasgow City Council|date=18 September 2014|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nA [[Survation]] poll the day prior to the election found that 71% of 2014 independence voters planned to vote for the SNP,<ref name=\"Survation final poll 2017\">{{cite web|url=http://survation.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Final-Daily-Record-Scotland-Poll-070617DCCH-1c0d0h1.pdf|title=Scotland Poll|work=Survation|date=7 June 2017|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref> significantly lower than the 87% of 'Yes' voters who were planning to vote SNP at a comparable time in 2015.<ref name=\"Survation final poll 2015\">{{cite web|url=http://survation.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Final-Daily-Record-May-Tables-1c6d6h0.pdf|title=Scottish Attitudes Poll May|work=Survation|date=6 May 2015|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref> A large amount of support from independence voters had moved to the Labour Party, with the party increasing their vote share among independence supporters from 6% to 21%.<ref name=\"Survation final poll 2017\"/><ref name=\"Survation final poll 2015\"/> The Conservatives had a smaller rise among independence supporters, gaining 7% of their votes in 2017, compared to 2% in 2015.<ref name=\"Survation final poll 2017\"/><ref name=\"Survation final poll 2015\"/>\n\nA realignment also occurred among those who opposed independence in the 2014 referendum. In 2015, Labour had the highest vote share among unionist voters at 42%.<ref name=\"Survation final poll 2015\"/> This dropped to 33% in 2017.<ref name=\"Survation final poll 2017\"/> The Conservatives became the largest anti-independence party increasing their votes from 27% to 46% of unionist voters.<ref name=\"Survation final poll 2017\"/><ref name=\"Survation final poll 2015\"/> Elsewhere, 11% backed the SNP and the Liberal Democrats in 2017, compared to 15% and 10% respectively in 2015.<ref name=\"Survation final poll 2017\"/><ref name=\"Survation final poll 2015\"/>\n\n=== United Kingdom general election, 2019 ===\n{{Main|2019 United Kingdom general election in Scotland}}\n[[File:2019UKelectionMapScotland.svg|thumb|266x266px|Results of the 2019 UK general election in Scotland]]\nThe [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 UK general election]] resulted in a majority parliament for the Conservatives led by Boris Johnson. The SNP held the position of third largest party in the House of Commons, gaining 13 seats from the previous election to a total of 48. The SNP garnered 45% of the popular vote in Scotland, an 8% gain from the 2017 UK general election.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2019-50766014|title=Scotland election results 2019: SNP wins election landslide in Scotland|last=|first=|date=Dec 13, 2019|work=BBC|access-date=Dec 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Nicola Sturgeon]], leader of the SNP, said: \"It couldn't really be any clearer from the results of this election that Scotland doesn't want a [[Boris Johnson]] government, it doesn't want to leave the European Union, and it wants to be able to determine its own future, whatever that future turns out to be.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/dec/14/sturgeon-scotland-wants-different-future-from-rest-of-uk|title=Sturgeon: Scotland wants different future from rest of UK|last=Gayle|first=Damien|date=Dec 14, 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=Dec 14, 2019}}</ref> This was in response to the Scottish Conservatives campaign, that, according to Sturgeon, focused solely on opposing a second referendum on Scottish Independence.<ref name=\":1\" /> Given Johnson's opposition to a second referendum, Sturgeon stated the Scottish Government could pursue a legal course of action to try to give the [[Scottish Parliament]] the power to call a referendum.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www-tmp.thenational.scot/news/18073959.sturgeon-take-legal-action-stop-johnson-indyref-block/|title=Sturgeon could take legal action to stop Johnson indyref block|last=Newsdesk|first=National|date=Dec 2, 2019|work=The National|access-date=Dec 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Procedure==\n{{Main|Referendums (Scotland) Act 2020}}\nWhile the Scottish Parliament could potentially hold an ''advisory'' referendum on the question of independence without the approval of the UK government, a ''binding'' referendum would require a section 30 order from the UK government, or an amendment to the Scotland Act 1998 by the UK Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ukconstitutionallaw.org/2017/03/13/stephen-tierney-a-second-independence-referendum-in-scotland-the-legal-issues/|title=Stephen Tierney: A Second Independence Referendum in Scotland: The Legal Issues|first=Constitutional Law|last=Group|date=13 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/second-referendum-scottish-independence|title=StackPath|website=www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Referendums Act===\nIn May 2019, the Scottish Government introduced the Referendums Bill to the Scottish Parliament as part of a three-tiered approach to constitutional change. This Bill, when passed, will form the statutory basis for all future referenda being held under Scots Law under the instruction of the Scottish Government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.scot/parliamentarybusiness/Bills/111844.aspx|title=Referendums (Scotland) Bill|date=2019-06-14|website=www.parliament.scot|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref> This legislation would form the legal basis of a further independence referendum. The current Scottish Government intends to seek a Section 30 order or an amendment to the Scotland Act 1998 to ensure that the result of a future referendum can be indisputably binding.\n\nThe Bill was passed at Stage 3 by the Scottish Parliament on 19 December 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-50288237|title=MSPs back principles of indyref2 framework bill|website=BBC News|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref>\n\n===Details===\nThe constitution is a 'reserved' matter of the United Kingdom government under the Scotland Act 1998. For a future referendum on Scottish independence to have a binding outcome, it would need to receive the consent of the British Government through a Section 30 order.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1998/46/contents|title=Scotland Act 1998|last=|first=|date=|website=Legislation.gov.uk|publisher=|access-date=25 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/scottish-independence-sorry-david-cameron-you-cant-prevent-second-referendum-scotland-1513014/|title=Scottish independence: Sorry David Cameron, you can't prevent a second referendum in Scotland|last=Kelly|first=James|date=|website=ibtimes.co.uk|publisher=[[International Business Times]]|access-date=25 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/politics/14580305.Scotland_put_on_stand_by_for_another_independence_referendum_after_Brexit_vote/|title=Scotland put on stand-by for another independence referendum after Brexit vote|last=Gardham|first=Magnus|date=25 June 2016|website=heraldscotland.com|publisher=[[The Herald (Scotland)|The Herald]]|access-date=25 June 2016}}</ref> The Scottish Parliament could approve a \"consultative referendum\" on the subject of independence, which would enable the referendum to take place without the approval of the British Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.scot/parliamentarybusiness/Bills/19017.aspx|title=Sewel Convention|date=2010-10-15|website=www.parliament.scot|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref> Under the Sewel Convention, the Scottish Government is able to issue a \"legislative consent motion,\" which would signal to the United Kingdom Parliament that Scottish Government has deemed it necessary to alter a law enacted by the UK Government or to change the scope of the devolved government's powers in some manner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.scot/parliamentarybusiness/CurrentCommittees/52668.aspx|title=Scrutiny of Legislative Consent Memorandum|last=Memoranda|first=Legislative Consent|date=2012-06-28|website=www.parliament.scot|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n===2016===\n[[Scottish Secretary]] [[David Mundell]] stated, on 26 June 2016, that \"if the people of Scotland ultimately determine that they want to have another [independence] referendum there will be one\", and added \"Could there be another referendum? The answer to that question is yes. Should there be another referendum? I believe the answer to that question is no.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/politics/scottish-politics/213848/second-independence-vote-is-publics-choice-mundell/|title=Scotland put on stand-by for another independence referendum after Brexit vote|last=McPherson|first=Gareth|date=26 June 2016|publisher=DC Thomson |work=[[The Courier (Dundee)|The Courier]]|access-date=26 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Nicola Sturgeon's -ScotRef announcement.webm|thumb|First Minister Sturgeon delivering her 13 March announcement]]\nOn 13 October 2016, Sturgeon announced that an Independence Referendum Bill will be published for consultation the following week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-37634338|title=SNP's Nicola Sturgeon announces new independence referendum bill|date=13 October 2016|website=bbc.com|publisher=BBC|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nOn 13 March 2017, Sturgeon announced she would seek Scottish Parliament approval to negotiate with the UK Government for a [[Section 30 of the Scotland Act|Section 30 order]] enabling a legally binding second independence referendum.<ref name=\"13marchscotgov\" />\n\nOn 16 March 2017, ahead of the scheduled debate, Theresa May responded by broadcasting a message where she said that \"now is not the time\" for a second referendum on Scottish independence, as it would be unclear what the people of Scotland would be voting for.<ref name=\"Rejected BBC 16Mar2017\"/> Ruth Davidson later appeared at a press conference in Edinburgh and stated her position that \"we will maintain that it should not take place when there is no clear public and political consent for it to happen\".<ref name=\"Rejected BBC 16Mar2017\" />\n\nThe debate began on 22 March 2017, but following that day's [[2017 Westminster attack|Westminster terrorist attack]], it was suspended before a vote could take place. The vote was subsequently rescheduled for 28 March, a day before Theresa May was scheduled to trigger Article 50.<ref>{{cite news |first= Severin |last=Carrell |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/mar/23/scottish-parliament-postpones-vote-second-independence-referendum |title= Scottish parliament postpones vote on second referendum |work= The Guardian |date= 23 March 2017 |accessdate= 24 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March 2017, the Scottish Parliament voted 69\u201359 on Motion S5M-04710, in favour of holding a second referendum on Scottish independence.<ref name=\"bbc-secondreferendum\">{{cite web|title=Scottish Parliament backs referendum call|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-39422747|website=BBC News|accessdate=28 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.scot/parliamentarybusiness/28877.aspx?SearchType=Advance&ReferenceNumbers=S5M-04710&ResultsPerPage=10|title=Motions, Questions and Answers Search|last=Office|first=Chamber|date=2016-06-16|access-date=2017-03-29}}</ref> Prior to the passage of the motion, a [[Scottish Green Party|Green Party]] amendment was passed, by the same margin, that seeks to enable 16 and 17 year-olds and EU citizens the opportunity to vote in a referendum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.scot/parliamentarybusiness/28877.aspx?SearchType=Advance&ReferenceNumbers=S5M-04710.5&ResultsPerPage=10|title=Motions, Questions and Answers Search|last=Office|first=Chamber|date=2016-06-16|access-date=2017-04-03}}</ref>\n\nThe full-motion, with the Green Party amendment in italics:\n\n<blockquote>That the Parliament acknowledges the sovereign right of the Scottish people to determine the form of government best suited to their needs and therefore mandates the Scottish Government to take forward discussions with the UK Government on the details of an order under section 30 of the Scotland Act 1998 to ensure that the Scottish Parliament can legislate for a referendum to be held that will give the people of Scotland a choice over the future direction and governance of their country at a time, and with a question and franchise, determined by the Scottish Parliament, which would most appropriately be between the autumn of 2018, when there is clarity over the outcome of the Brexit negotiations, and around the point at which the UK leaves the EU in spring 2019''; believes that this gives people in Scotland a choice at a time when there is both the most information and most opportunity to act; further believes that 16 and 17-year-olds and EU citizens, who were excluded from the EU referendum, should be entitled to vote, and considers that this referendum is necessary given the Prime Minister\u2019s decision to negotiate a hard exit from the EU, including leaving the single market, which conflicts with assurances given by the UK Government and prominent Leave campaigners, and which takes no account of the overwhelming Remain vote in Scotland.''</blockquote>\n\nFollowing the 2017 UK general election, Sturgeon announced that the Scottish Government would postpone legislation on the proposed second referendum on Scottish independence until at least autumn 2018, when it was believed that the outcome of Brexit negotiations would become clearer.<ref name=NicolaDelays>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-40415457 |title= Nicola Sturgeon puts Scottish independence referendum bill on hold|work=[[BBC]]|date= 27 June 2017 |accessdate= 27 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nOn 25 May 2018, the Scottish National Party published its \"Growth Commission\" report, which detailed the economics of an independent Scotland when maintaining close alignment to British fiscal policy. The report noted that it would take \u00a3450 million to set up an independent state, with an initial budget deficit of around 6% of GDP. The report, additionally, suggested that an independent Scotland would negotiate a share of the UK national debt, while continuing to use the [[Pound Sterling]] as currency for at least a decade. Scotland would only consider an independent currency, once certain economic goals had been met. Despite not having a separate currency on independence, the report suggested that Scotland would set up a central bank to act as a lender of last resort. According to the Growth Commission, Scotland would seek an open migration policy to allow for its population to grow.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-44237956|title=What's in the SNP's growth commission report?|work=BBC News|date=25 May 2018|accessdate=6 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nScottish Conservative leader Ruth Davidson responded to the report by saying: \"For me, the most important issue is making sure our children get a good education. The first minister used to claim that that was her priority too\u2014how times have changed. It's hard to see how dragging Scotland back down the rabbit hole of a debate on independence is going to improve our schools.\" Richard Leonard, Scottish Labour's leader, stated that the report, \"will exasperate millions of people around the country who just want the first minister focused on public services\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-44224884|title=Scotland 'can match top small countries'|work=BBC News|date=24 May 2018|accessdate=6 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nIn March 2019, the SNP conference adopted an amendment version of the Growth Commission as party policy on the economics of independence.  This amended version established that it is now SNP policy for an independent Scotland to create a new currency at the earliest feasible point of independence to enable fiscal sovereignty, with Pound Sterling being a transitional currency for Scotland.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-48069470|title=SNP members change leadership's currency plan|date=2019-04-27|access-date=2019-06-16|language=en-GB}}</ref> First Minister Sturgeon also announced the establishment of a 'Social Justice Commission' to develop the social argument for independence to complement the SNP's new economic policy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/bbf70b34-69c7-11e9-80c7-60ee53e6681d|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Sturgeon proposed holding a second referendum before the end of the Scottish Parliamentary session in May 2021.<ref name=\"Sturgeon 2019\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-48026430 |title=Scottish independence: Sturgeon wants indyref2 by 2021 |work=BBC|date= 24 April 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> Legislation has been introduced in the form of the 'Referendums (Scotland) Bill' to govern future referenda, on any subject, in Scotland held by the Scottish Government. The Scottish Government is working on a three-pronged approach to constitutional change:\n\n*Firstly, a referendum on independence through the Referendums (Scotland) Bill is a matter of intent of the government to allow Scotland a say on independence.\n*Secondly, cross-party talks are to be held to enable any areas of agreement on changes to devolution to be explored.\n*Lastly, the Scottish Government is establishing the [[Citizens' Assembly of Scotland]] to discuss the most prominent issues faced by contemporary Scottish governance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gapi.io/6OUb|title=Citizens' Assembly of Scotland|website=Scottish Government News|language=english|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref>\n\nThe civic campaign group [[Voices for Scotland]] launched in April 2019 to secure a pro-independence majority in Scotland through societal engagement. This group was established by the [[Scottish Independence Convention]] which is made up of cross-party and grassroots organisations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/indyref2-campaign-group-launches-with-elaine-c-smith-on-board-1-4914657|title=Indyref2: Campaign group launches with Elaine C Smith on board|website=www.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref>\n\nOn the same day as the passing of the [[Referendums (Scotland) Act 2019]], Nicola Sturgeon officially published the Scottish Government's request to Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] for the transfer of legal authority to hold a referendum on independence. This request set out the constitutional history of Scotland's place in the United Kingdom and that the Scottish Government would deem either a Section 30 order or an amendment to the Scotland Act as a satisfactory means of transferring the power over independence referendums.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/publications/scotlands-right-choose-putting-scotlands-future-scotlands-hands/|title=Scotland's right to choose: putting Scotland's future in Scotland's hands - gov.scot|website=www.gov.scot|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref> Sturgeon's intention is for the referendum to be held in 2020.<ref name=\"for 2020\">{{cite news |first= Libby |last=Brooks |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/15/nicola-sturgeon-to-demand-powers-for-2020-referendum |title= Nicola Sturgeon to demand powers for 2020 referendum |work= The Guardian |date= 15 October 2019 |accessdate= 31 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\nSturgeon's 2019 request was rejected by the UK government in January 2020.<ref name=\"bbc2020\">{{cite web|title=Scottish independence: Johnson rejects Sturgeon's indyref2 demand|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-51106796|website=BBC News|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref> In his official response, Johnson wrote that Sturgeon and Salmond had promised that the 2014 referendum would be a \"once in a generation\" vote, that both the Scottish and UK governments had pledged to implement the outcome of that vote, and that his government therefore \"cannot agree to any request for a transfer of power that would lead to further independence referendums\".<ref name=\"bbc2020\" />\n\nThe Scottish Parliament passed a motion introduced by the Scottish Government on 29 January 2020 to endorse a new referendum on independence. The motion was carried 64 votes to 54.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/scotland/scottish-parliament-independence-indyref2-vote-rebuffed-1379613|title=Scottish Parliament backs indyref2 this year \u2014 but is swiftly rebuffed|website=inews.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> This was on the same day that the Parliament resolved to continue flying the [[Flag of Europe]] after the UK's withdrawal from the European Union.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/brexit-msps-vote-to-keep-flying-eu-flag-at-scottish-parliament-after-heated-debate-1-5082706|title=Brexit: MSPs vote to keep flying EU flag at Scottish Parliament after heated debate|website=www.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n== Issues ==\n===Scotland's future relations with the EU and EEA===\n{{Brexit sidebar}}\n[[File:United Kingdom EU referendum 2016 area results.svg|thumb|The results of the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|European Union membership referendum]] by voting areas. Scotland, [[Northern Ireland]], [[London]], and [[Gibraltar]] voted in majority to remain in the [[European Union]], contrasting with Wales and the rest of England, who ultimately carried the result of [[United Kingdom withdrawal from the European Union|leaving]].<br />{{legend|#0069b5|Leave}} {{legend|#ffc010|Remain}}]]\nFollowing the EU referendum result, Sturgeon said she would communicate to all EU member states that Scotland had voted to stay in the EU.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2016/jun/23/eu-referendum-result-live-counting-leave-remain-brain-in-europe|title=Nicola Sturgeon says second Scottish referendum 'highly likely' \u2013 as it happened|date=24 June 2016|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> An emergency Scottish cabinet meeting on 25 June 2016 agreed that the Scottish Government would seek to enter negotiations with the EU and its member states, to explore \"options to protect Scotland's place in the EU\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jun/25/sturgeon-seeks-urgent-brussels-talks-to-protect-scotlands-eu-membership|title=Sturgeon to lobby EU members to support Scotland's bid to remain|first1=Severin|last1=Carrell|first2=Jennifer|last2=Rankin|date=25 June 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"stv250616\">{{cite web |url=http://stv.tv/news/politics/1358598-sturgeon-to-seek-eu-talks-to-protect-scotland-s-memebrship/ |title=Sturgeon to seek EU talks to 'protect' Scotland's membership |first=Aidan |last=Kerr |work=STV News |publisher=STV |date=25 June 2016 |accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref> On 28 June 2016, Sturgeon said that \"independence [...] is not my starting point in these discussions. My starting point is to protect our relationship with the EU.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=Press Association<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Nicola Sturgeon says independence vote would be proposed 'if best or only way to protect EU place'|url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/politics/scottish-politics/215192/nicola-sturgeon-says-independence-vote-proposed-best-way-protect-eu-place/ |newspaper=The Courier |location=Dundee, Scotland |date=28 June 2016 |access-date=28 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter a summit of EU leaders on 29 June 2016, Sturgeon held meetings with some EU officials.<ref name = \"greenland\"/> She raised the possibility of parts of the UK remaining within the EU, or for these areas to have special arrangements with the EU, after the UK leaves.<ref name = \"greenland\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-scotland-greenland-idUSKCN0ZJ08R |title='Reverse Greenland', anyone? Scots eye post-Brexit EU options |work=Reuters |first1=Alastair |last1=MacDonald |first2=Elisabeth |last2=O'Leary |date=3 July 2016 |accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref> [[David Edward]], a former justice of the [[European Court of Justice]], suggested that these arrangements would relate to policy areas that have been devolved to Scotland.<ref name = \"greenland\"/>\n\nSturgeon also met European Commission president [[Jean-Claude Juncker]], who commented that \"I will listen carefully to what the first minister will tell me... but we don't have the intention, neither [[Donald Tusk]] nor myself, to interfere in an inner British process that is not our duty and this is not our job.\"<ref name = \"rajoy2906\"/> [[Manfred Weber]], leader of the [[European People's Party Group]], and [[Guy Verhofstadt]], leader of the [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Group]], indicated that they were supportive of Scotland remaining an EU member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/fastft/2016/06/24/scotland-n-ireland-can-stay-in-eu-says-merkel-ally/|title=Fast FT|first=FT|last=Membership|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=GuyVerhofstadt |number= 746302049927708672|date= 24 June 2016|title= It's wrong that Scotland might be taken out of EU, when it voted to stay. Happy to discuss w. @NicolaSturgeon next time she's in Bxl. #EUref|author=Guy Verhofstadt |author-link= Guy Verhofstadt}}</ref><ref name=\"Herald Scotland 26-6-16\">{{cite web | title=EU leaders tell UK 'hurry up and leave' | website=Herald Scotland | url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/homenews/14580576.EU_leaders_tell_UK___39_hurry_up_and_leave__39_/ | accessdate=26 June 2016 | quote=Guy Verhofstadt, highlighted Scotland's case to remain, saying that it was \"wrong\" that the country faced being pulled out of the EU despite 62 per cent of the population voting to remain}}</ref> [[Gunther Krichbaum]], head of the Bundestag's Committee for EU Affairs, made supportive comments about Scotland becoming a member state of the EU.<ref>{{cite web|last=Carrel|first=Paul|title=Scotland welcome to join EU, Merkel ally says|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-scotland-germany-idUSKCN0ZC0QT|website=Reuters.com|date=26 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Prime Minister of Spain|Spanish Prime Minister]] [[Mariano Rajoy]] said: \"[be] very clear Scotland does not have the competence to negotiate with the European Union\".<ref name = \"rajoy2906\"/> He also stated his opposition to the EU negotiating with \"anyone other than the government of United Kingdom\" and that \"if the United Kingdom leaves... Scotland leaves\".<ref name = \"rajoy2906\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-36656980 |title=Brexit: Spain and France oppose Scotland EU talks |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=29 June 2016 |accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref> Similarly, the [[President of France|French President]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]], stated: \"The negotiations will be conducted with the United Kingdom, not with a part of the United Kingdom\".<ref name = \"rajoy2906\"/>\n\nThe Scottish European and External Affairs Committee held an evidence session on 30 June 2016, asking a panel of four experts (Dr Kirsty Hughes of [[Friends of Europe]], Prof Sionaidh Douglas-Scott of the Queen Mary School of Law at the [[University of London]], Sir David Edward and Prof Drew Scott of the [[University of Edinburgh]]) what they felt was the best way to secure the Scottish-EU relationship.<ref name = \"experts\"/> Hughes stated that \"the simplest and most obvious way would be to be an independent state and transition in and stay in the EU\", Douglas-Scott said that \"Legally there are precedents. [...] But there were also political difficulties\", referring to [[Catalonia]] in member state Spain. Edward believed \"Scotland makes quite a good fit with Iceland and Norway\", referring to the [[European Economic Area]] and the [[European Free Trade Association]], while Scott hinted that Scotland could be a successor state, meaning the rest of the UK would leave but Scotland would retain its seat.<ref name = \"experts\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-36673126 |title=Brexit: Scottish independence 'simplest EU option' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=30 June 2016 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe new UK Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] met with Sturgeon on 15 July 2016 in [[Edinburgh]], when May stated that she was \"willing to listen to options\" for Scotland,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-36800536 |title=Brexit: PM is 'willing to listen to options' on Scotland  |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=15 July 2016 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> although she later stated that some options were \"impracticable\".<ref name = \"ippr\"/> Sturgeon then publicly stated that she had five tests for any future arrangements.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-36878081 |title=Brexit: Sturgeon sets out key Scottish interests that 'must be protected' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=25 July 2016 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> The [[IPPR]] thinktank stated that [[Unionism in Scotland|Scottish unionists]] needed to provide options for Scotland, if they wished to retain the British union.<ref name = \"ippr\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-36877869 |title=Think tank says unionists must offer Scotland EU options |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=24 July 2016 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> The [[Scottish Labour Party]] published an 'Action Plan' in July 2016, focusing on the economy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-36897565 |title=Scottish Labour publish Brexit economy 'action plan' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=27 July 2016 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn their manifestos for the [[2017 German federal election]], the [[Free Democratic Party (Germany)|Free Democrats]] and the [[Alliance 90/The Greens|Greens]] stated that EU membership would remain an option for Scotland and Northern Ireland (as well as for the rest of the UK), if they left the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-08-30/german-parties-snub-u-k-to-back-scotland-s-push-to-defy-brexit |title=German Parties Snub U.K. to Back Scotland's Push to Defy Brexit |first=Alan |last=Crawford |work=Bloomberg |publisher= |date=30 August 2017 |accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, a report for the [[European Parliament Committee on Constitutional Affairs]] was published to look at the implications on the UK's withdrawal from the European Union on Scotland, Wales and Gibraltar and their future relations with the EU. The report suggested that Scotland would be unlikely to be rejected as a member of the EU, should it become independent, noting that \"not since [[Charles de Gaulle|de Gaulle\u2019s]] veto on UK membership in the 1960s has a democratic country respecting the rule of law been refused admission\". However, it affirmed that Scotland's independence would have to be accepted by the United Kingdom for Scotland to obtain EU membership: \"There now seems to be a consensus that, were Scotland to become independent by legal means, it could join the [European] Union\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/IDAN/2017/583118/IPOL_IDA%282017%29583118_EN.pdf|title=The Impact of the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union on Scotland, Wales and Gibraltar|first=Michael|last=Keating|publisher=[[European Parliament]]|date=April 2017|accessdate=6 December 2018|page=19}}</ref>\n\n====Possible EFTA membership====\nIn November 2016, Sturgeon confirmed to members of the Scottish Parliament that the Scottish Government was considering joining the [[European Free Trade Association]] (EFTA) and the [[European Economic Area]] (EEA), based on the model of [[Norway]] and some other countries, to \"protect [Scotland's] place in the single market\" of Europe even if the United Kingdom as a whole does leave in a \"hard [[Brexit]]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-37993028|title=Nicola Sturgeon confirms 'Norway model' option|date=2016-11-16|newspaper=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref> The SNP's 2017 General Election manifesto stated that \"the Scottish Government [led by the SNP, had] published proposals that would keep Scotland in the Single Market, even as we left the EU.\"<ref>''Scottish National Party Manifesto 2017''. p. 8.</ref> Christophe Hillion, a Professor of European Law at the [[University of Oslo]] who was invited to deliver an expert opinion to the Scottish Parliament, said that while there is scepticism about UK accession to EFTA in Norway, Scotland is viewed much more positively, and that the EFTA member states would likely welcome an independent Scotland as a member.<ref name=\"thenat\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenational.scot/news/16097931.eea-likely-to-welcome-an-independent-scotland/|title=EEA 'likely to welcome' an independent Scotland|date=2018-03-20|work=The National}}</ref>\n\n===Legislative consent in disapplying EU law===\nThe [[Scotland Act 1998]] empowers the [[Scottish Parliament]] to legislate in policy areas devolved to Scotland, but one of its clauses obliges the Scottish Parliament to ensure its legislation is compatible with European law.<ref name=\"taylor 260616\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-36635012|title=Could the Scottish Parliament stop the UK from leaving the EU?|last=Taylor|first=Brian|date=26 June 2016|publisher=BBC|work=BBC News|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Renwick\">{{cite news|url=http://europe.newsweek.com/could-scotland-really-veto-brexit-474963|title=Could Scotland Really Veto Brexit?|last=Renwick|first=Alan|date=27 June 2016|work=Newsweek|publisher=|accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref> For the UK to completely leave the EU, it would need to remove that obligation.<ref name=\"Renwick\" /> If the UK Parliament wishes to legislate on policy areas devolved to Scotland, or if it wishes to amend the powers devolved to Scotland, by convention it needs the Scottish Parliament to pass a \"[[legislative consent motion]]\".<ref name=\"taylor 260616\" /><ref name=\"Renwick\" /> On 26 June 2016, Sturgeon said she would ask the Scottish Parliament to withhold consent if she thought it was not in Scotland's interests.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36633371|title=Nicola Sturgeon: Scotland could veto Brexit|date=26 June 2016|publisher=BBC|work=BBC News}}</ref> Giving evidence to a House of Lords committee before the EU referendum, [[David Edward]] suggested the consent of the Scottish Parliament would be needed for this legislation.<ref name=\"taylor 260616\" />\n\nMedia reports suggested this might give the Scottish Parliament a veto over UK withdrawal from the EU,<ref name=\"taylor 260616\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/scotland/holyrood-may-exercise-veto-m93tgd3b6|title=Holyrood may exercise veto|last=Allardyce|first=Jason|date=26 June 2016|work=The Times}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2016/6/25/12031254/no-brexit-article-50|title=\"Bracksies\": how Brexit could wind up not actually happening|last=Matthews|first=Dylan|date=25 June 2016|website=vox.com}}</ref> but under the Scotland Act 1998 the UK Parliament could ultimately override the \"veto\" as it is based only on parliamentary convention.<ref name=\"taylor 260616\" /><ref name=\"Renwick\" /> Alternatively, the UK Parliament could choose to disregard the obligation for the Scottish Parliament to observe EU law.<ref name=\"Renwick\" /> The then Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, [[Theresa Villiers]], said that the UK Government would consult with the devolved governments and noted that it was for the UK Parliament to decide whether to leave the EU by repealing the [[European Communities Act 1972 (UK)|European Communities Act 1972]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-36633939|title=EU referendum: Theresa Villiers says parliament sovereign|date=26 June 2016|publisher=BBC|work=BBC News|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref> In its ruling in the [[R (Miller) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|case]] brought by [[Gina Miller]] regarding the UK Government's authority to invoke Article 50, the [[UK Supreme Court]] unanimously ruled that the devolved governments did not have a veto as the convention was unenforceable in law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-38721650|title=Supreme Court Brexit ruling: What happens next?|date=25 January 2017|publisher=BBC|work=BBC News|accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref> Speaking later that week the Secretary of State for Scotland, [[David Mundell]], said that the bill needed to invoke Article 50 would not require consent, but also said he was working under the assumption that the \"Great Repeal Bill\" needed to remove European legislation from UK statutes would require co-operation from the devolved bodies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-38757264|title=Mundell: Holyrood to be consulted on Great Repeal Bill|date=26 January 2017|publisher=BBC|work=BBC News|accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Responses to the prospect of a referendum==\n:''See also, for comparison [[2014 Scottish independence referendum#Responses]]''\nResponses by politicians to the possibility of a second referendum have been pro-independence (and pro-referendum), pro-union, or pro-federalism.\n\n====In support of a referendum====\n\nScottish Greens co-convener [[Patrick Harvie]], on 13 March 2017 welcomed the confirmation from the First Minister that she is seeking a Section 30 Order from the UK Government to give the Scottish Parliament temporary power to call a referendum on independence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://greens.scot/news/greens-welcome-referendum-call|title=Greens Welcome Referendum Call|date=2017-03-13|work=Scottish Greens|access-date=2017-03-13|language=en}}</ref> This was re-affirmed in the Scottish Parliament on 29 January 2020 when the Greens voted with the government for a referendum to be held.\n\n[[Scottish Socialist Party]] spokesman [[Colin Fox (political activist)|Colin Fox]] said the SSP would \"work as hard as anyone to deliver a Yes vote for independence\", but warned that making Scotland's EU membership a central and \u201coverarching\u201d issue of the debate would be \u201ca risky strategy\u201d and said it ran the risk of side-lining economic and social challenges facing Scots.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenational.scot/news/15153561.Pro_independence_parties_throw_their_weight_behind_ScotRef_decision/|title=Pro-independence parties throw their weight behind ScotRef decision|date=14 March 2017|accessdate=14 March 2017|publisher=The National}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/13/nicola-sturgeon-could-derail-brexit-scottish-referendum-demand/|title=Theresa May rules out Nicola Sturgeon's plans for a new Scottish independence referendum before Brexit, as Lords pass landmark Brexit bill following MPs' vote|date=13 March 2017|accessdate=14 March 2017|newspaper=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Scottish Independence Convention]] backs calls for a referendum. As a result, the Convention established [[Voices for Scotland]] as a civic campaign for independence based on conversations and discussions of what Scotland could look like. <ref>{{cite news |url=https://bellacaledonia.org.uk/2018/09/18/announcing-a-new-national-campaign/ |title=Announcing a New National Campaign |first=Robin |last=McAlpine |work=Bella Caledonia |publisher=Bella Caledonia |date=18 September 2018 |accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.commonspace.scot/articles/13296/new-campaign-organisation-aims-take-independence-movement-next-level |title=New campaign organisation aims to take independence movement 'to the next level' |first=Sean |last=Bell|work=CommonSpace |publisher=CommonSpace |date=18 September 2018 |accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nA few days before the 2017 General Election, Sturgeon was asked about the prospect of a third referendum if the proposed second one did not result in a vote in favour of independence.<ref name=\"PandJ\">{{cite news|url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/news/politics/westminster/general-election/1261080/nicola-sturgeon-jeered-refusing-rule-third-independence-referendum-within-years/|title=Nicola Sturgeon jeered after refusing to rule out third independence referendum within a few years|date=6 June 2017|accessdate=6 June 2017|newspaper=The Press and Journal}}</ref> She refused to rule out a third referendum within a few years, saying that, \"I don't think it's right for any politician to dictate to a country what its future should be. I think that should be a choice for the people of Scotland.\"<ref name=\"PandJ\" />\n\nAlison Evison, President of the [[Convention of Scottish Local Authorities]] (COSLA) and [[Scottish Labour]] councillor for Aberdeenshire has stated her support for a referendum on independence, stating \"We can strengthen it [democracy] by enabling the voice of Scotland to be heard through its formal processes and that must mean a referendum on independence\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sundaypost.com/fp/labour-councillor-and-cosla-president-calls-for-second-independence-referendum/|title=Labour councillor and Cosla president calls for second independence referendum|last=Post|first=The Sunday|website=Sunday Post|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\nFormer First Minister [[Alex Salmond]] has shown support for a further independence referendum, claiming it is inevitable but only after what he predicts will be the \u2018humiliation\u2019 of Brexit becomes apparent for a clear choice to be made.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/alex-salmond-scottish-independence-indyref-brexit-humiliation-snp-a7887236.html|title=Alex Salmond calls for second independence referendum after Brexit 'humiliation'|date=2017-08-10|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n====Opposed to a referendum====\n\n=====British party leaders=====\nIn November 2019 during the lead up to the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|UK general election]], leader of the Conservatives and Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] stated that a conservative government would not permit a second independence referendum, vowing to \"protect our magnificent union\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/newsscotland/boris-johnson-wont-give-scots-a-second-independence-referendum/ar-BBXlKhO|title=Boris Johnson won't give Scots a second independence referendum|last=Bussey|first=Katrine|date=Nov 26, 2019|work=MSN|access-date=Dec 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFormer Labour Party leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] said in March 2017 that a referendum would be \"absolutely fine\" and that \"I don't think it's the job of Westminster or the Labour Party to prevent people holding referenda.\" However, a spokesman for Corbyn later said: \"Labour continues to oppose a further referendum in the Scottish Parliament and would campaign against independence if one were held.\"<ref name=\"BBC News Corbyn 2017\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-39244890|title=Scottish independence: Jeremy Corbyn says indyref2 'absolutely fine'|date=11 March 2017|website=BBC News|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] leader [[Tim Farron]] in March 2017, said: \u201cScottish Liberal Democrats stood for election last year on a platform to oppose a new independence referendum. That is what we will do.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.libdems.org.uk/scottish_liberal_democrats_will_oppose_second_referendum|title=Scottish Liberal Democrats will oppose second referendum|last=http://www.libdems.org.uk/|date=2017-03-13|work=Liberal Democrats|access-date=2017-03-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA spokesperson speaking on behalf of Cameron's successor as Conservative Party Leader and Prime Minister, [[Theresa May]], said in October 2016: \"The prime minister and the government does not believe that there is a mandate for [a second referendum]. There was one only two years ago. There was an extremely high turnout and there was a resounding result in favour of Scotland remaining in the UK.\"<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-37708545|title=New Scottish independence bill published|date=20 October 2016|work=BBC}}</ref>\n\n=====Scottish party leaders=====\nInterim [[Scottish Conservatives|Scottish Conservative]] leader [[Jackson Carlaw]] has stated his opposition to a referendum. He has said; \"We will not support another independence referendum for a generation.\" and that the Scottish Government should focus on its domestic agenda. He has stated that 40 years is what he sees as the time needed between referenda.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/election-2019-50588843|title=General election 2019: Jackson Carlaw answers your questions on the election|website=BBC News|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n[[Scottish Labour]] leader [[Richard Leonard (Scottish politician)|Richard Leonard]] is against a referendum on independence. He has stated that Scotland should seek a new devolution settlement rather than becoming an independent country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/opinion/columnists/why-it-s-time-for-home-rule-for-scotland-richard-leonard-1-5081354|title=Why it's time for Home Rule for Scotland \u2013 Richard Leonard|website=www.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> However, Leonard has said that [[UK Labour Party]] policy on independence and a referendum should be decided by the Scottish branch of the party rather than by the whole UK party. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/newsscotland/richard-leonard-tells-labour-chiefs-scottish-party-will-decide-indyref2-position/ar-BBZ4PkQ|title=Richard Leonard tells Labour chiefs Scottish party will decide IndyRef2 position|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n[[Scottish Liberal Democrats]] leader [[Willie Rennie]] said in March 2017, \"We stood on a platform last May where we said we were against independence and against another independence referendum\",<ref name=\"MACMAHON 2017\">{{cite web | title=Rennie: My MPs will vote to block indyref2 | website=ITV News | date=11 March 2017 | url=http://www.itv.com/news/border/2017-03-11/rennie-my-mps-will-block-indyref2/ | accessdate=2 April 2017 | last=MACMAHON | first=PETER}}</ref> he also said, \"No independence referendum, either at Westminster or in the Scottish Parliament \u2013 that's the view of the Liberal Democrats.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-39248104|title=Willie Rennie wants Scottish independence poll blocked|date=2017-03-12|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-03-17|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Opinion polling==\n{{see also|Opinion polling on Scottish independence|Scottish Independence#Public opinion|Opinion polling for the Scottish independence referendum, 2014}}\n[[File:IndependentScotland.png|thumb|440x440px|Results of polls to 31 January 2020]]\nIn nearly every opinion poll following the EU membership referendum, participants are asked to respond to the question or subtle variation of:\n\n<blockquote>If the referendum was held again tomorrow, how would you vote in response to the question: ''Should Scotland be an independent country?''</blockquote>\n\nutilising the final six words (in italics) as in the 2014 referendum question. A response of \"Yes\" therefore is for Scottish independence and response of \"No\" for remaining in the United Kingdom.\n\nPolls vary in how weightings are applied (methods of which are not described by the polling organisations) and in which participants are excluded from the final data (based on how likely they are to vote). There is an inherent \u00b1 3% [[margin of error]] based on a sample size of ~1,000.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center; line-height: 14px;