a/polls/SundayTimesScottishtablesforpublication250616.pdf Panelbase/''Sunday Times''] || 626 ||style=\"background: rgb(153, 255, 153);\"|'''47%'''||44%||8%||style=\"background: rgb(0, 129, 66); color: white;\"| {{ntsh|3}}3% ||\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-06-25\" |25 Jun 2016\n|Online\n|Yes||[http://survation.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/Post-Brexit-Scottish-Attitudes-Poll.pdf Survation/''Daily Record''] ||1,002 ||style=\"background: rgb(153, 255, 153);\"|'''48%'''||41%||9%||style=\"background: rgb(0, 129, 66); color: white;\"| {{ntsh|7}}7% ||\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-06-24\" |24 Jun 2016\n| colspan=\"9\" |'''[[David Cameron]] resigns as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]]''' <br /> '''[[Nicola Sturgeon]] announces her government would draft legislation for a second independence vote'''\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-06-23\" |23 Jun 2016\n| colspan=\"9\" |'''[[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]]'''\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2014-09-17\" style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| ''18 Sep 2014'' \n| colspan=\"3\" |''[[2014 Scottish independence referendum]]'' ''results''|| style=\"background:#D5D5D5\" | 3,623,344 || style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"| ''44.7%'' || style=\"background: rgb(220, 36, 31); color:white;\" | '''''55.3%''''' || style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"|  || style=\"background: rgb(220, 36, 31); color: white;\" | {{ntsh|-10.6}}''10.6%'' ||\n|}\n\n===Three-option polling===\nBefore the Scottish independence referendum in 2014, some three option opinion polls were conducted, giving respondents the option of full independence, some (undefined) form of [[Full fiscal autonomy for Scotland|increased devolution]] and the status quo. One poll of this type has been conducted since the EU membership referendum.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center; line-height: 14px; font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Date(s)<br />conducted\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Polling organisation/client\n!Independence\n!Devo Max\n!Status Quo\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Undecided\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: rgb(0, 129, 66); width: 100px; color: white;\" |  !! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: orange; width: 100px; color: white;\" | !! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: rgb(220, 36, 31); width: 100px; color: white;\" |\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2018-01-28\" | 24\u201328 Jan 2018 ||[https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/poll-support-for-scottish-independence-at-32-1-4683018/amp Survation/Scottish Independence Referendum Party]||| 32% || 15% || style=\"background: rgb(248, 193, 190);\" |'''36%'''|| 17% \n|}\n\n====Independence & EU polling====\nSince 2014, Scotland has voted both to remain within the United Kingdom and the European Union. Since the UK's vote to leave the EU, opinion polls have been conducted that asks whether voters would prefer for Scotland to become independent to remain in the EU or for Scotland to remain in the UK and leave the EU.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"  style=\"text-align:center; line-height:14px; font-size:95%; width:800px;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20%;\" rowspan=\"2\"|Date(s)<br />conducted\n! style=\"width:35%;\" rowspan=\"2\"|Polling organisation/client\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Independence within the EU\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Remain in the UK and leave the EU\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Undecided\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: rgb(0, 129, 66); width: 100px; color: white;\" |  !! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: rgb(220, 36, 31); width: 100px; color: white;\" | !! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background:gray; width:100px; color:white;\"|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2018-06-27\" | 21\u201327 Jun 2018 || [https://www.drg.global/wp-content/uploads/F12183-Scottish-Poll-tables-for-publication-270618.pdf Panelbase/Wings Over Scotland] ||| 42% || style=\"background: rgb(248, 193, 190);\" |'''44%''' || 14%\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2017-12-20\" | 15\u201320 Dec 2017 || [https://www.drg.global/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/F11548TablesForPublication020118.pdf Panelbase/Wings Over Scotland] ||| 39% || style=\"background: rgb(248, 193, 190);\" |'''40%''' || 21%{{refn|group=lower-alpha|Includes voters who would not vote \u2013 10% were undecided; 11% would not vote.}}\n|}\n;Notes\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n===Regional opinion polling===\n====[[Edinburgh South (UK Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh South]]====\nEdinburgh South had the highest proportion of Remain votes of any parliamentary constituency in Scotland outside of [[Glasgow North (UK Parliament constituency)|Glasgow North]] and [[Edinburgh North and Leith (UK Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh North and Leith]] at the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]] at 77.8% Remain 22.2% Leave.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center; line-height: 14px; font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Date(s)<br />conducted\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Polling organisation/client\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Sample size\n!Yes \n!No\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Undecided\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Lead\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Notes\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: rgb(0, 129, 66); width: 100px; color: white;\" | !! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: rgb(220, 36, 31); width: 100px; color: white;\" |\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2017-06-08\" | 8 Jun 2017 || colspan=\"10\" | '''[[2017 United Kingdom general election]]''' \n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2017-04-04\" | 3\u20134 April 2017 || [http://survation.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/Final-Edinburgh-South-Tables-5c3d0h-030417JSCH-sba.pdf Survation/Stop Brexit Alliance] || 530 || 34% || style=\"background: rgb(233, 107, 103); color: white;\" | '''55%''' || 10% || style=\"background: rgb(220, 36, 31); color: white;\" | 21% || Excludes 16 and 17 year-olds\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2014-09-17\" style=\"background:#D5D5D5\" | ''18 Sep 2014'' || style=\"background:#D5D5D5\" | ''[[Politics of Edinburgh#Scottish Independence referendum|Scottish independence referendum, 2014]] results'' || style=\"background:#D5D5D5\" | 58,738 || style=\"background:#D5D5D5\" | ''34.7%'' || style=\"background: rgb(220, 36, 31); color:white;\" | '''''65.3%''''' || style=\"background:#D5D5D5\" |  || style=\"background: rgb(220, 36, 31); color: white;\" | ''30.6%'' ||\n|}\n\n===Hypothetical polls conducted before the EU referendum===\nBefore the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]], there were some opinion polls conducted which asked people if they would vote for Scottish independence in the (then hypothetical) event of a \"leave\" vote in that referendum.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center; line-height: 14px; font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Date(s)<br />conducted\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Polling organisation/client\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Sample size\n!Yes \n!No\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Undecided\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Lead\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: rgb(0, 129, 66); width: 100px; color: white;\" | !! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: rgb(220, 36, 31); width: 100px; color: white;\" |\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-06-23\" |23 Jun 2016\n| colspan=\"6\" |'''[[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]]'''\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-06-16\" |6\u201316 Jun 2016 || [http://storage.pardot.com/36112/187064/TNS___EU_Referendum_Poll__Scotland____2_June_2016.pdf{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} TNS]|| 1,008|| 43% || style=\"background: rgb(248, 193, 190);\" | '''46%''' || 9% || style=\"background: rgb(220, 36, 31); color: white;\" | 3%\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-05-10\" |6\u201310 May 2016 || [https://www.icmunlimited.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ICM_Scotland-Poll_May-2016-v2.pdf ICM/''The Scotsman'']|| 1,000|| 44% || style=\"background: rgb(248, 193, 190);\" | '''47%''' || 9% || style=\"background: rgb(220, 36, 31); color: white;\" | 3%\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-04-28\" |23\u201328 Apr 2016|| [https://web.archive.org/web/20160610033109/http://panelbase.com/media/polls/W7181w6tablesforpublication280416.pdf Panelbase/''Sunday Times'']||1,074||style=\"background: rgb(153, 255, 153);\"|'''47%'''||44%||9%||style=\"background: rgb(0, 129, 66); color: white;\"|3%\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-04-15\" | 6\u201315 Apr 2016 || [https://web.archive.org/web/20160513130808/http://panelbase.com/media/polls/W7181w5ScottishSundayTimesApril2016PolltablesForPublication150416.pdf Panelbase/''Sunday Times'']|| 1,021 ||style=\"background: rgb(153, 255, 153);\"|'''46%'''||45%||9%||style=\"background: rgb(0, 129, 66); color: white;\"|1%\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2016-02-07\" |1\u20137 Feb 2016|| [https://www.ipsos-mori.com/researchpublications/researcharchive/3699/SNP-remains-dominant-while-Brexit-could-swing-Scots-behind-a-second-independence-referendum-Yes-vote.aspx Ipsos Mori/STV] || 1,000 ||style=\"background: rgb(1, 223, 116);\"|'''54%'''||39%||7%||style=\"background: rgb(0, 129, 66); color: white;\"|15%\n|}\n\n===On the prospect of a second referendum===\n==== 2017 ====\nAnalysis of opinion polling from early 2017 by Professor [[John Curtice]] found that around 50% of Scottish voters were opposed to the holding of a second referendum on Scottish independence, with just over a third in support of holding another referendum.<ref>[http://blog.whatscotlandthinks.org/2017/03/does-scotland-want-a-second-independence-referendum/ 'Does Scotland Scotland want a second independence referendum?']</ref>\n\nA September 2017 poll by Survation gave respondents an option of when they thought a second referendum should be held. 22% said that they'd support holding a referendum before Britain leaves the European Union, 13% said around the time Britain leaves the EU, a further 13% said that a referendum should be held a few years following the UK's exit and 8% said a referendum should come after the [[2021 Scottish Parliament election|2021 Scottish Parliamentary elections]]. 37% said that a referendum should never be held on Scottish independence again, with 8% undecided.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://survation.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Final-SDM-VI-Tables-1c0d1h6-080917MBJRFSTJNHCH-I.pdf|title=Voting Intention Poll|work=Survation|date=13 September 2017|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nA Panelbase poll from the same month found that 17% of people thought that a referendum should be held while the UK is negotiating its exit from the European Union, 26% said that a referendum should come once the negotiations had finished, while 58% said that a referendum shouldn't be held before the United Kingdom's exit from the EU.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panelbase.com/media/polls/W7181w14forpublication070917.pdf|title=Sunday Times (W7181w14)|work=Panelbase|date=7 September 2017|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== 2018 ====\nIn January 2018, YouGov found that 54% of people opposed holding a referendum in principle, compared to 36% who supported holding one. These numbers fell when asked whether a referendum should be held following Brexit negotiations, but before the UK leaves the EU, to 51% and 35% respectively. The same poll found that 36% supported holding a referendum once Britain has left the EU, compared to 47% opposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://d25d2506sfb94s.cloudfront.net/cumulus_uploads/document/une1vahaj1/TimesResults_180116_Westminster_Scotland_VI_w.pdf|title=YouGov / The Times Survey Results|work=YouGov|date=12\u201316 January 2018|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nA March 2018 poll by Ipsos Mori found that 42% of Scots supported holding a second referendum within the next three years, compared to 47% who opposed one; 8% said that they neither supported or opposed a referendum being held within this timescale. Support for a referendum was highest among sixteen to thirty-four year-olds, the unemployed, charity workers, council house dwellers and people living in the 20% of most deprived areas in Scotland. Opposition was greatest from people aged over fifty-five, retirees, homeowners and people with no formal qualifications.<ref name=\"Ipsos Mori March 2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ipsos.com/sites/default/files/ct/news/documents/2018-03/scotland-spom-march-2018-tables.pdf|title=Scottish Public Opinion Monitor \u2013 Wave 35|work=Ipsos Mori|date=5\u201311 March 2018|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Opinion polling in the rest of the United Kingdom ===\nIn 2014 a plurality (41%) of people polled in England and Wales thought that Scotland would vote to remain in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news |last=Learmonth |first=Andrew |date=8 July 2016 |title=Majority of Brits believe Scots would vote to exit UK |url=http://www.thenational.scot/news/majority-of-brits-believe-scots-would-vote-to-exit-uk.19740 |newspaper=The National |location= |access-date=8 July 2016 }}</ref> However, an [[Opinium Research LLP|Opinium]] poll carried out 28\u201330 June 2016 showed a marked change, with 69% believing that Scotland would vote for independence in a second referendum, with 16% believing it would vote against independence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ourinsight.opinium.co.uk/sites/ourinsight.opinium.co.uk/files/vi_28_06_2016_v2.pdf |title=Opinium VI 28 06 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704154110/http://ourinsight.opinium.co.uk/sites/ourinsight.opinium.co.uk/files/vi_28_06_2016_v2.pdf |archivedate=4 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nA May 2018 poll, conducted by Panelbase, suggested that 52% of English-born English-based voters would vote to enter into a political union with Scotland if the countries were independent of each other, compared to 58% supporting a union with Wales and 43% with Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wingsoverscotland.com/the-island-within-an-island/|title=The island within an island|date=18 May 2018|accessdate=19 May 2018|publisher=Wings Over Scotland}}</ref> The poll additionally found that 43% of English voters would accept Scotland leaving the United Kingdom as a result of the exit from the European Union, compared to 35% who would oppose this.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wingsoverscotland.com/nations-overboard/|title=Nations Overboard|date=17 May 2018|accessdate=19 May 2018|publisher=Wings Over Scotland}}</ref>\n\n=== Opinion polling in the European Union ===\nPolls conducted by YouGov in July 2016 found majority support in Germany (71%), Denmark (67%), Finland (66%), Sweden (64%) and France (61%) for Scotland becoming an EU member should it become an independent state, with plurality support in EFTA member Norway (46%) and the United Kingdom as a whole (41%).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://yougov.de/news/2016/07/08/nach-der-brexit-entscheidung-deal-or-no-deal/ |title=Nach der Brexit-Entscheidung: Deal or no Deal? |first=Matthias |last=Schmidt |website=yougov.de |publisher=YouGov |date=8 July 2016 |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Unionism in Scotland]]\n*[[Irish reunification]]\n*[[Welsh independence]]\n*[[London independence]]\n*[[All Under One Banner]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Scottish elections}}\n{{United Kingdom European Union membership referendum, 2016}}\n\n[[Category:Consequences of the 2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|Scottish independence]]\n[[Category:Independence referendums|Scottish independence referendum]]\n[[Category:Proposed referendums|Scottish independence referendum]]\n[[Category:Referendums in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scottish independence]]\n", "name_user": "Lorgadh", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eUnited Kingdom general election, 2019)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proposed_second_Scottish_independence_referendum"}
